<p>
where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumbe=
r/Inline31.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:=
100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"33" height=3D"21" alt=3D"P(s)">
 is the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PrimeZetaFunction.html">pr=
ime zeta function</a> and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/=
equations/PrimeNumber/Inline32.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-he=
ight:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"22" height=3D"21" alt=3D"[S=
]"> is an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/IversonBracket.html">Ive=
rson bracket</a>.
</p>
<p>
The function that gives the number of primes less than or equal to a number=
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inl=
ine33.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%"=
 border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> is denoted <img src=3D"h=
ttps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline34.svg" cla=
ss=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" =
width=3D"32" height=3D"21" alt=3D"pi(n)"> and is called the <a href=3D"http=
s://mathworld.wolfram.com/PrimeCountingFunction.html">prime
 counting function</a>. The theorem giving an asymptotic form for <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline35.svg=
" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=
=3D"0" width=3D"32" height=3D"21" alt=3D"pi(n)"> is called the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://mathworld.wolfram.com/PrimeNumberTheorem.html">prime
 number theorem</a>. Similarly, the numbers of primes of the form <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline36.svg=
" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=
=3D"0" width=3D"50" height=3D"21" alt=3D"ak+b"> less than or equal to a num=
ber <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/=
Inline37.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:10=
0%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> is denoted <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline38.svg=
" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=
=3D"0" width=3D"48" height=3D"23" alt=3D"pi_(a,b)(n)"> and is called the <a=
 href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ModularPrimeCountingFunction.html">m=
odular
 prime counting function</a>.
</p>
<p>
<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inli=
ne39.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" =
border=3D"0" width=3D"32" height=3D"21" alt=3D"pi(n)"> and <img src=3D"http=
s://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline40.svg" class=
