<p>
The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/FundamentalTheoremofArithmetic=
.html">fundamental theorem of arithmetic</a> states that any <a href=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/PositiveInteger.html">positive integer</a> can b=
e represented
 in <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ExactlyOne.html">exactly one</=
a> way as a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Product.html">product<=
/a>
 of primes. <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/EuclidsTheorems.html">=
Euclid's second theorem</a> demonstrated
 that there are an infinite number of primes. However, it is not known if t=
here are
 an infinite number of primes <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Ofth=
eForm.html">of the form</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/image=
s/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline43.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-=
height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"44" height=3D"21" alt=3D"=
n^2+1"> (Hardy and Wright 1979, p.&nbsp;19; Ribenboim 1996, pp.&nbsp;206-20=
8),
 whether there are an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Infinite.htm=
l">infinite</a> number of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/TwinPrim=
es.html">twin
 primes</a> (the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/TwinPrimeConjectu=
re.html">twin prime conjecture</a>), or
 if a prime can always be found between <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfr=
am.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline44.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" s=
tyle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D=
"21" alt=3D"n^2"> and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equa=
tions/PrimeNumber/Inline45.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height=
:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"54" height=3D"21" alt=3D"(n+1)^=
2"> (Hardy and Wright 1979, p.&nbsp;415; Ribenboim 1996,
 pp.&nbsp;397-398). The latter two of these are two of <a href=3D"https://m=
athworld.wolfram.com/LandausProblems.html">Landau's
 problems</a>.
</p>
<p>
The simplest method of finding factors is so-called "<a href=3D"https://mat=
hworld.wolfram.com/DirectSearchFactorization.html">direct search factorizat=
ion</a>" (a.k.a. <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/TrialDivision.htm=
l">trial division</a>).
 In this method, all possible factors are systematically tested using trial=
 division
 to see if they actually <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Divide.ht=
ml">divide</a> the given number. It is
 practical only for very small numbers. More general (and complicated) meth=
ods include
 the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/EllipticCurveFactorizationMet=
hod.html">elliptic curve factorization
 method</a> and <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/NumberFieldSieve.h=
tml">number field sieve</a> factorization
 method.
</p>
<p>
It has been proven that the set of prime numbers is a <a href=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/DiophantineSet.html">Diophantine
set</a> (Ribenboim 1991, pp.&nbsp;106-107).
</p>
<p>
With the exception of 2 and 3, all primes are of the form <img src=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline46.svg" class=
=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" wi=
dth=3D"82" height=3D"21" alt=3D"p=3D6n+/-1">, i.e., <img src=3D"https://mat=
hworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline47.svg" class=3D"inli=
neformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"1=
17" height=3D"21" alt=3D"p=3D1,5 (mod 6)"> (Bungus 1599, p.&nbsp;399, quote=
d in Peano 1908,
 p.&nbsp;59; Wells 1986, p.&nbsp;68). For <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wol=
fram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline48.svg" class=3D"inlineformula"=
 style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=
=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Integer.html=
">integer</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Pr=
imeNumber/Inline49.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;ma=
x-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"28" height=3D"21" alt=3D"&gt;=3D2">, <i=
mg src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline=
50.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bo=
rder=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> is prime <a href=3D"https:/=
/mathworld.wolfram.com/Iff.html">iff</a> the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.w=
olfram.com/CongruenceEquation.html">congruence
 equation</a>
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/PrimeNumber/NumberedEquation5.svg" class=3D"numberedequation"=
 style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"162" height=
=3D"41" alt=3D" (n-1; k)=3D(-1)^k (mod n) "></td><td align=3D"right" width=
=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn8" class=3D"eqnum">
(8)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
holds for <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeN=
umber/Inline51.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wi=
dth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"21" alt=3D"k=3D0">,
 1, ..., <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNu=
mber/Inline52.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"37" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n-1">
 (Deutsch 1996), where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equ=
ations/PrimeNumber/Inline53.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heigh=
t:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"31" height=3D"43" alt=3D"(n; k=
)">
 is a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/BinomialCoefficient.html">bi=
nomial coefficient</a>. In addition, an
 integer <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNu=
mber/Inline54.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">
 is prime <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Iff.html">iff</a>
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/PrimeNumber/NumberedEquation6.svg" class=3D"numberedequation"=
 style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"126" height=
=3D"20" alt=3D" phi(n)+sigma(n)=3D2n. "></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3=
">
<div id=3D"eqn9" class=3D"eqnum">
(9)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
The first few composite <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eq=
uations/PrimeNumber/Inline55.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heig=
ht:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">
 for which <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Prime=
Number/Inline56.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-w=
idth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"119" height=3D"24" alt=3D"n|[phi(n)+sigma(=
n)]">
 are <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber=
/Inline57.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:1=
00%" border=3D"0" width=3D"57" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n=3D312">, 560, 588, 14=
00, 23760, ... (OEIS
 <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A011774">A011774</a>; Guy 1997), with a total o=
f 18 such
 numbers less than <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equatio=
ns/PrimeNumber/Inline58.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:10=
0%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"51" height=3D"21" alt=3D"2=C3=9710=
^7">.
</p>
<p>
Chen (1979) showed that for <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/image=
s/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline59.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-=
height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x=
"> sufficiently large, there always exists a number with at least
 two prime factors between <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images=
/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline60.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-h=
eight:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"45" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x=
-x^alpha">
 and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber=
/Inline61.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:1=
00%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x"> for <img src=3D"http=
s://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline62.svg" class=
=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" wi=
dth=3D"91" height=3D"21" alt=3D"alpha&gt;=3D0.477..."> (Le Lionnais 1983, p=
.&nbsp;26; Guy 2004,
 p.&nbsp;34). In practice, this relation seems to hold for all <img src=3D"=
https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/PrimeNumber/Inline63.svg" cl=
ass=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0"=
 width=3D"64" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x&gt;2521">.
</p>
<p>
Primes consisting of consecutive <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/D=
igit.html">digits</a> (counting 0 as coming after 9) include 2, 3, 5, 7, 23=
, 67, 89, 4567, 78901, ... (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A006510">A00651=
0</a>).
 Primes consisting of digits that are themselves primes include 23, 37, 53,=
 73, 223,
 227, 233, 257, 277, 337, 353, 373, 523, 557, ... (OEIS <a href=3D"http://o=
eis.org/A019546">A019546</a>),
 which is one of the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SmarandacheSe=
quences.html">Smarandache sequences</a>.
</p>
<p>
Because a prime number <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equ=
ations/PrimeNumber/Inline64.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heigh=
t:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" alt=3D"p">
 has only the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Trivial.html">trivia=
l</a> factors 1 and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equati=
ons/PrimeNumber/Inline65.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:1=
00%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" alt=3D"p">, in =
his <i><a href=3D"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0670772895/ref=3Dn=
osim/ericstreasuretro">The
 Road Ahead</a></i>, Bill Gates accidentally referred to a trivial operatio=
n when
 he stated "Because both the system's privacy and the security of digital m=
oney
 depend on encryption, a breakthrough in mathematics or computer science th=
at defeats
 the cryptographic system could be a disaster. The obvious mathematical bre=
akthrough
 would be the development of an easy way to <i>factor large prime numbers</=
i> [emphasis
 added]" (Gates 1995, p.&nbsp;265).
</p>
